Power and Cooling

The power required to run a new AI model training data center has the potential to be more than an average nuclear power plant can produce. Tech companies that have pledged to reduce their carbon footprint have actually increased it. For example, reports show that Microsoft’s footprint has increased by nearly 30% since 2020 and many are pointing at AI as the source of this increase.

Some individuals hope that AI can eventually help in the quest to achieve long-term environmental sustainability. However, at this point, AI could be doing more harm than good. Based on one study, training an AI model produces more CO2 than the average 55-year-old will have produced since birth.

It is imperative that organizations working to advance AI do it in an environmentally responsible manner. The three primary areas in which organizations can reduce AI-generated power and cooling requirements are hardware optimization, software efficiency, and data center management.

Hardware Optimization

It is less efficient to use a CPU for a task that an AI accelerator can accomplish. There are several types of specialized hardware, such as VPUs, ASICs, TPUs, NPUs, and more that have lower power requirements than more general-use processors.

Dynamic resource management is another method to reduce power consumption. A method called power capping places limits on the amount of energy a device can use, preventing high levels of energy from being used during peak load times. Another method, Dynamic Voltage with Frequency Scaling (DVFS) reduces power consumption by dynamically adjusting the voltage and frequency of processors based on the current workload. Lastly, Computational Random-Access Memory (CRAM) is currently still in the research phase, but the results are extremely promising. CRAM processes data within memory cells, eliminating the need to transfer it between logic and memory modules. Initial testing shows a 2500 times reduction in power consumption over traditional methods.

Software Efficiency

AI software efficiency refers to the ability of AI algorithms, models, and applications to perform tasks with optimal use of resources like computational power. The primary way software efficiency can be attained with AI is through optimizing the AI model.

The major aspects of model optimization include the following techniques:

  • Quantization: Involves adjusting the precision of the model numbers such as using 8-bit integers instead of 32-bit integers.

  • Model Pruning: The practice of removing unused neural network parameters to help reduce the model size while maintaining performance.

  • Knowledge Distillation: Trains a smaller model to behave like a larger model. The smaller model is considered the student, while the larger model is the teacher. Since the student model is smaller, it will require less energy.

Data Center Management

There are several factors to consider when attempting to reduce power consumption in an AI data center. There is no single method that can be implemented to achieve an adequate solution, but by strategically implementing multiple methods, a significant reduction in energy usage can be achieved.

To effectively manage a data center, an organization must have processes in place to monitor energy usage. Monitoring goes beyond simply checking the total power usage at the end of the month. Instead, monitoring includes implementing systems that continually monitor power usage on a device level to dynamically optimize usage based on workload.

Organizations must also consider where they are getting their power from can be more important than how much they are using. For example, a data center powered by a coal-burning power plant will produce a much higher CO2 output than one running on solar.

Lastly, for data centers to run reliably, their components must be kept cool. Devices designed for AI produce a lot of heat. Estimates vary, but most agree that the cost of cooling AI-specific devices can account for 30-40% of the energy consumption of a data center.
